## Silent S t r i  be r s

The Silent Striders are wanderers, messengers and travelers; more than anything else they are enigmas.  Though the tribe originally hails from Egypt, they no longer  reside there, instead wandering the globe. Though it is claimed that no Garou can enter the lands of the dead, the scent of the Dark Umbra clings to  them.  And  though  they  rarely  do  any  other  Garou  wrong,  few werewolves completely trust the Silent Striders.

activity, the  Silent  Striders are welcome visitors  at  nearly  any caem. If  rumors  are  to be  believed,  the  Striders  even find  welcome among the fae and wizards of the world, and ghosts are said to follow them. When wandering the world, the Striders have an uncanny tendency to poke their snouts in where they don't  belong  and  come  out  with  trouble  o n their tails. This may be the reason they are so widely distrusted. Most Striders make a li acting  as  couriers  or  messengers  betw caerns;  they  know  the hidden  byways \ enough, and, it is rumored, afew secret Mc Bridges to boot. When acting  as messengers or bearing tidings  of  the Wyrm's

With the usual exception of Banes ar Black  Spiral  Dancers,  the  Striders  hol their greatest hatred for vampires. Triba legend holds that the Striders fought an army of  vampires led by  a dark undead godling called Sutekh. Sutekh supposedly cast a great curse on the tribe that drove them from Egypt, scattered them to  the winds, and worst  of  all,  severed their bonds with their ancestors. Since tl- many Striders take  Egyptian names as a their past, and search the Umbra in vain fc of  their forbears.

The Silent Striders do have a relatic t h e  Restless Dead. T h e  origin of  the re12 unknown, but Striders tend to attract g b tion when passing through the Gauntlet of the Umbra. Rare is the Silent Strider m have at least one wraith tagging along as Out of a sense of respect and politeness, t will generally avoid mentioning such gho of strangers.

